  "prompt": "What should I do to get selected in GSOC 2018?",
  "response": "Google Summer of Code (GSoC) is a highly competitive program, and getting selected requires a combination of preparation, engagement, and outright skill. Here are some steps you can follow:\n\n1. **Understand GSoC**: Familiarize yourself with how GSoC works \u2013 its timeline, the organizations involved, and the kind of projects typically offered.\n\n2. **Choose the Right Organization**: Look through the list of participating organizations and select the ones that align with your interests and skills. Research their previous projects and see the kind of work they\u2019ve done.\n\n3. **Engage Early**: Start interacting with the organizations early. Join their mailing lists, participate in their IRC chats, forums, and Slack channels.\n\n4. **Contribute to the Community**: Begin by contributing small patches or bug fixes. This will help you get noticed and show your interest.\n\n5. **Improve Your Skills**: Make sure your coding skills are strong enough for your chosen project. Practice writing clean, efficient code and make sure you\u2019re comfortable with version control systems like Git.\n\n6. **Build a Strong Proposal**: Write a detailed proposal that outlines your project plan, timeline, and milestones. Make sure to explain why you are a good fit for the project.\n\n7. **Communicate Effectively**: Show your enthusiasm and willingness to learn. Communicate regularly with potential mentors and ask for feedback on your proposal.\n\n8. **Apply Early**: Don\u2019t wait until the last minute to submit your application. This gives you more time to refine your proposal and respond to any potential mentor feedback.\n\n9. **Follow Instructions**: Make sure to follow all the application instructions carefully. Missing a step or requirement can result in disqualification.\n\n10. **Keep Trying**: If you don\u2019t get selected, ask for feedback and keep contributing to open-source projects. The experience will be invaluable for future applications.\n\nRemember, persistence and active engagement with the community are key to making a successful application. Good luck!",
